Certain British regional accents pronounce "th" as "f." You hear it a lot in Cockney, and also in Birmingham/"Brummie" dialect. "Oi bruvver, oi fink fings ain't what dey used to be, innit? Keef bought us free pints" etc.

Linguists call it "th-fronting." It is heard mainly among lower-class people. Announcers on the BBC aren't going to talk like this. Middle and upper class people regard it as sounding uneducated and inarticulate. Americans and Canadians think it sounds hilarious, like Mr. Gumby from a Monty Python sketch.
